coverage of terror attacks to viral videos of police brutality, and from graphic horror films to transgressive artworks, many of the images in our media culture might strike us as unsuitable for viewing. Yet what does it mean to proclaim something “unwatchable”: disturbing, revolting, poor, tedious, or literally inaccessible? With over 50 original essays by leading scholars, artists, critics, and curators, this is the first book to trace the “unwatchable” across our contemporary media environment, in which viewers encounter difficult content on various screens and platforms. Appealing to a broad academic and general readership, the volume offers multidisciplinary approaches to the vast array of troubling images that circulate in global visual culture.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 21. Jun 2021) 0aImage (Philosophy). 0aMass media and the arts. 0aRepresentation (Philosophy). 0aVisual communicationxPsychological aspects. 0aVisual perceptionxPhilosophy. 7aPERFORMING ARTS / General.2bisacsh1 aBaer, Nicholas, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBaer, Nicholas, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aBalsom, Erika, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBalsom, Erika.1 aBerger, Kenneth, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBerger, Kenneth.1 aBoyce Gillespie, Michael, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBright, Susie, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBright, Susie.1 aBush, Alex, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBush, Alex.1 aButler, Alec, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aButler, Alec.1 aCarroll, Noel.1 aCarroll, Noël, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/